{{infobox organization | name = Harleian Society | image = File:Harleian_Soc_logo.gif | image_border = | size = 150 | map = | msize = | mcaption = | alt = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] --> | caption = | formation = 1869 | type = [[Historical society]] | status = Charity | registration_id = 253649 | purpose = Heraldic study and research | headquarters = London, United Kingdom | leader_title = Activities | leader_name = Research and publications | leader_title2 = Collections | leader_name2 = Library, archives | leader_title3 = President | leader_name3 = [[Thomas Woodcock (officer of arms)|Thomas Woodcock]] | website ={{url|harleian.org.uk}} }}
'''The Harleian Society''' is a [[text publication society]] and [[registered charity]] founded in 1869 for the publication of manuscripts of the [[heraldic visitation]]s of the counties of England and Wales, and other unpublished manuscripts relating to [[genealogy]], [[Armory (heraldry)|armory]], and [[heraldry]] in its widest sense. Since its inception, the Society has published more than 90 volumes of [[parish register]]s, 54 volumes of heraldic visitations, and 70 volumes drawn from other sources.
The Society's publications are available by [[subscription business model|subscription]].
The Society was named after the [[Harleian Collection|Harleian Manuscripts]], originally accumulated by [[Robert Harley, 1st Earl of Oxford and Earl Mortimer|Robert Harley, 1st Earl of Oxford]], and his son [[Edward Harley, 2nd Earl of Oxford and Earl Mortimer|Edward Harley, 2nd Earl of Oxford]], and now held in the [[British Library]], which include many copies of heraldic visitations.
==See also== *[[Heraldry]] *[[College of Arms|The College of Arms]]
